## Overview

Implement a `Binding.of[A]` macro that derives bindings independently of Schema derivation. This enables:
1. Cleaner separation of concerns
2. Reuse of binding derivation logic
3. Schema.derived macro can delegate binding creation to this macro

## API Design

```scala
object Binding {
  // For proper types (case classes, sealed traits, primitives, concrete collections)
  transparent inline def of[A]: Any = ${ ofImpl[A] }

  // For sequence type constructors
  inline def of[F[_]](using sc: SeqConstructor[F], sd: SeqDeconstructor[F]): Binding.Seq[F, Nothing] = 
    new Binding.Seq(sc, sd)

  // For map type constructors  
  inline def of[M[_, _]](using mc: MapConstructor[M], md: MapDeconstructor[M]): Binding.Map[M, Nothing, Nothing] = 
    new Binding.Map(mc, md)
}
```

Scala 2 equivalent using `implicit` instead of `using`.

## Type Handling Matrix

| Input Type | Return Type | Implementation |
|------------|-------------|----------------|
| `Int`, `String`, etc. primitives | `Binding.Primitive[A]` | Return existing vals from `Binding.Primitive` |
| Case class `Person` | `Binding.Record[Person]` | Generate Constructor/Deconstructor |
| Sealed trait/enum `Color` | `Binding.Variant[Color]` | Generate Discriminator/Matchers |
| `Option[A]` | `Binding.Variant[Option[A]]` | Use `Binding.Variant.option[A]` |
| `Either[A, B]` | `Binding.Variant[Either[A, B]]` | Use `Binding.Variant.either[A, B]` |
| `None.type` | `Binding.Record[None.type]` | Use `Binding.Record.none` |
| `Some[A]` | `Binding.Record[Some[A]]` | Use `Binding.Record.some[A]` or specialized vals |
| `Left[A, B]` | `Binding.Record[Left[A, B]]` | Use `Binding.Record.left[A, B]` |
| `Right[A, B]` | `Binding.Record[Right[A, B]]` | Use `Binding.Record.right[A, B]` |
| `List[Int]` | `Binding.Seq[List, Int]` | `Binding.of[List]` upcast via covariance |
| `Vector[String]` | `Binding.Seq[Vector, String]` | `Binding.of[Vector]` upcast via covariance |
| `Map[K, V]` | `Binding.Map[Map, K, V]` | `Binding.of[Map]` upcast via covariance |
| `DynamicValue` | `Binding.Dynamic` | Return `Binding.Dynamic()` |
| Opaque type | `Binding.Wrapper[A, Underlying]` | Dealias, derive underlying, wrap |
| ZIO Prelude newtype | `Binding.Wrapper[A, Underlying]` | Dealias, derive underlying, wrap |
| Smart constructor type | `Binding.Wrapper[A, Underlying]` | Detect pattern, derive underlying, wrap |
| `List` (type constructor) | `Binding.Seq[List, Nothing]` | From implicit SeqConstructor/SeqDeconstructor |
| `Map` (type constructor) | `Binding.Map[Map, Nothing, Nothing]` | From implicit MapConstructor/MapDeconstructor |

## Smart Constructor Detection

Detect types with companion `apply` method returning `Either[E, A]`:

```scala
case class Email private (value: String)
object Email {
  def apply(v: String): Either[String, Email] = 
    if (isEmail(v)) Right(new Email(v)) else Left(s"$v is not a valid email")
}
```

For such types, generate `Binding.Wrapper[Email, String]`:
- `wrap`: Call `Email.apply`, convert `Left[E]` to `SchemaError` (if E is already SchemaError, use as-is; otherwise call `.toString`)
- `unwrap`: Extract underlying value (`_.value` for single-field case classes)

This pattern also covers:
- Scala 3 opaque types with smart constructors
- ZIO Prelude newtypes (use baked-in knowledge of their structure)

