Given a key K and a value V with a schema for each, I want to create a schema for a tuple `(K, V)` in a generic way.

```scala
def tupleSchema[K, V](k: Reflect.Bound[K], v: Reflect.Bound[V]): Reflect.Record.Bound[(K, V)] = {
  val temp = Reflect.Record[Binding, (K, V)](
    fields = Vector(k.asTerm("_1"), v.asTerm("_2")),
    typeName = TypeName(Namespace(Nil, Nil), "Tuple"),
    recordBinding = Binding.Record(constructor = null, deconstructor = null)
  )
  Reflect.Record[Binding, (K, V)](
    fields = temp.fields,
    typeName = temp.typeName,
    recordBinding = Binding.Record(
      constructor = new Constructor[(K, V)] {
        def usedRegisters: RegisterOffset                                = temp.usedRegisters
        def construct(in: Registers, baseOffset: RegisterOffset): (K, V) =
          (
            temp.registers(0).get(in, baseOffset).asInstanceOf[K],
            temp.registers(1).get(in, baseOffset).asInstanceOf[V]
          )
      },
      deconstructor = new Deconstructor[(K, V)] {
        def usedRegisters: RegisterOffset                                             = temp.usedRegisters
        def deconstruct(out: Registers, baseOffset: RegisterOffset, in: (K, V)): Unit = {
          temp.registers(0).asInstanceOf[Register[Any]].set(out, baseOffset, in._1)
          temp.registers(1).asInstanceOf[Register[Any]].set(out, baseOffset, in._2)
        }
      }
    )
  )
}
```
Notice how i made a dummy `Record` (`temp`) just so that I could use it to implement `constructor` and `deconstructor`?
Without this trick, I have to reimplement `registers` entirely, which is not possible because methods like `RegisterOffset.incrementBooleansAndBytes` are private.

Is there a better way to achieve this? I feel like there should be one.

